Lurikeen I agree that prisons shouldn't be a resort, but I think a lot of the idea that they are comes from media induced fear and the pols perpetual cries for stronger punishment. The ones who cry the most for it are the ones who are also getting good contributions from places like <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.wcc-corrections.com/wcc-corrections/corporateprofile.html">Wackenhut</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. Unfortunately because prisons and privatization are inherently good in our eyes we never <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://serendipity.magnet.ch/more/palast01.htm">see</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. what really goes on there, even when it has direct effect on us. As for the recreation outlets, lurikeen and kylien, those are there as part of a larger plan to calm the prisoners and remind them that they are apart. <br>
<br>
Here is a little funny excert from Live From Death Row, by Mumia Abu Jamal;<br>
Setup:A prisoner doesn't want his television instead he wants to write. <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> One inmate, more interested in life than entertainment, argued forcefuly with prison administrators for permission to buy nonimpact, non-metallic, battery operated typewriter. Predictable permission was denied for security reasons. &quot;Well what do y'all consider a thirteen-inch piece of glas?' the prisoner asked. &quot;Ain't that a security risk?&quot;<br>
&quot;where do you think you'll get that from&quot; the prison official demanded.<br>
&quot;From my TV&quot;<br>
Request for typewriter denied.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
